### Try-Catch-Finally Blocks

The try-catch-finally construct provides structured exception handling in C#.

### Basic Try-Catch

```csharp
try
{
    // Code that may throw exceptions
    int result = int.Parse("not-a-number");
}
catch (FormatException ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Invalid format: {ex.Message}");
}
```

### Multiple Catch Blocks

```csharp
try
{
    int.Parse(input);
}
catch (FormatException)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Invalid number format");
}
catch (OverflowException)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Number is too large");
}
catch (Exception)
{
    Console.WriteLine("An error occurred");
}
```

### Finally Block

Always executes regardless of exceptions:

```csharp
FileStream? file = null;
try
{
    file = File.OpenRead("data.txt");
    // Read file
}
catch (FileNotFoundException ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"File not found: {ex.Message}");
}
finally
{
    file?.Close();  // Always executed
    Console.WriteLine("Cleanup complete");
}
```

### Try-Catch-Finally Flow

| Scenario | try | catch | finally |
|----------|-----|-------|---------|
| No exception | Executes fully | Skipped | Executes |
| Exception caught | Stops at exception | Executes | Executes |
| Exception uncaught | Stops at exception | Skipped | Executes, then propagates |

### Using Statement (IDisposable)

A cleaner alternative to try-finally for resources:

```csharp
using (var file = File.OpenRead("data.txt"))
{
    // Use file - auto-disposed at end
}

// Using declaration (C# 8+)
using var reader = new StreamReader("data.txt");
string content = reader.ReadToEnd();
// Disposed at end of scope
```

### Nested Try Blocks

```csharp
try
{
    try
    {
        // Inner operation
    }
    catch (InvalidOperationException innerEx)
    {
        // Handle inner exception
    }
}
catch (Exception outerEx)
{
    // Handle outer exception
}
```

### Exception Filters (when)

```csharp
try { Process(); }
catch (HttpException ex) when (ex.StatusCode == 404)
{
    // Only catch 404 errors
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use `finally` to clean up resources (close files, connections). `catch` blocks are checked in order - catch specific exceptions before general ones. Use `using` for IDisposable resources instead of manual try-finally. The `finally` block always executes, even if there's a return statement in try.

### Try-Catch as Expression

```csharp
int result;
try
{
    result = int.Parse(input);
}
catch
{
    result = 0;
}
```

### Throw in Finally

Avoid throwing exceptions in finally blocks - it can mask the original exception.

codeExample:
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string path = "test.txt";

        try
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Attempting to read file...");
            string content = File.ReadAllText(path);
            Console.WriteLine(content);
        }
        catch (FileNotFoundException)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"File '{path}' not found");
        }
        catch (IOException ex)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"IO error: {ex.Message}");
        }
        finally
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Operation completed");
        }
    }
}
